\begin_layout Section
Solow Model 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Output is a simple (Cobb-Douglas) production function of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
Y & =F(K,L)\label{eq:productionFunction}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=output$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K,L$
\end_inset

 are capital and labour.
 Since Cobb-Douglas is a constant-return-to-scale function (CRS), we can
 simplify above as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{{Y}}{L}=F(\frac{{K}}{L},1)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\frac{{Y}}{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\frac{{K}}{L}$
\end_inset

, then we can rewrite 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:productionFunction"

\end_inset

 as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
y & =F(k,1)=f(k)\label{eq:K_over_L}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To introduce saving and investment in this model we consider that consumption
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $C=(1-s)Y$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s=savings\ rate$
\end_inset

.
 If we don't have any government (investing or consuming) in the model (see
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:national_income"

\end_inset

), then we can assume that all savings are invested within the society in
 the state of equilibrium (society invests its savings within the society).
 
\begin_inset Formula $I=sY$
\end_inset

.
 This would also mean that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
i & =sY=sf(k)\label{eq:investment_output}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that capital depreciates at a constant rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

, we have net change in capital at any (sparse) time point as
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta K=I-\delta K$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 change in capital over an year).
 Note that this condition is independent of whatever production function
 is chosen.
 This is useful in deriving steady state conditions.
 Using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:investment_output"

\end_inset

, one can write the following: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
\Delta k & =sf(k)-\delta k\label{eq:kapital_depreciation}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can argue that in steady state i.e.
 capital doesn't depreciate any more (no capital is really saved when all
 of it is reinvested).
 This would mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta k=0$
\end_inset

 and lead to: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
i & =sf(k^{*})=\delta k^{*}\label{eq:steadyStateOutputCapialDep}
\end{align}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that there are two key assumptions in the theory so far.
 First, that 
\bar under
all savings are reinvested
\bar default
 (so that 
\begin_inset Formula $sY=I$
\end_inset

 ) and second (similar assertion) that capital depreciation 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta k$
\end_inset

 equals investment (
\begin_inset Formula $i=sy)$
\end_inset

.
 The second assumption is the steady-state condition.
 Therefore, it should not be assumed that the economy gravitates towards
 golden rule i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $MPK=\frac{\partial F}{\partial K}=\delta$
\end_inset

 (it's not part of the steady state assumptions).
\end_layout

