, a couple of observations can be made:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Loss of capital would mean the output would fall.
 But if savings rates stay high, then the loss is limited and capital would
 grow back up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When savings rate increases in a steady-state economy, the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $i=s\cdot f(k)$
\end_inset

 shifts upwards while capital and depreciation stay the same.
 Hence the income increases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remember that in such caes, we don't jump to the next steady state immediately.
 Instead we talk about the transitory period.
 When savings decrease, we use 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}f(k^{*})=(n+\delta)k^{*}.$
\end_inset

 If new savings rate 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}<s_{0}$
\end_inset

, then right off we'll have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}f(k)<s_{0}f(k)=(n+\delta)k$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta k=s_{1}f(k)-(n+\delta)k<0$
\end_inset

.
 The immediate effect is therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta k<0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general policies that raise income per individual are said to have a
 growth effect while the policies that increase saving rates are said to
 have a level effect (as only the level of income per person is affected
 by savings rate).
 
\end_layout

