\end_inset

.
 The golden rule becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*}=f(k^{*})-(\delta+n)k^{*}$
\end_inset

 which is optimized at 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial F}{\partial K}=\delta+n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introducing technology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Introducing technology changes the output function as 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=F(K,L\cdot E)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is the efficiency of labour.
 A better technology would have a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and would require less labour (number of workers) for the same output level.
 Changing definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\frac{K}{L\cdot E}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\frac{Y}{L\cdot E},$
\end_inset

we maintain the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:K_over_L"

\end_inset

 and write the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
\Delta k & =s\cdot f(k)-(\delta+n+g)\cdot k\label{eq:solow_tech_pop}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The golden rule thus becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*}=f(k^{*})-(\delta+n+g)k^{*}$
\end_inset

which is optimized at 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial F}{\partial K}=\delta+n+g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With technology and population, the Solow model.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y/L$
\end_inset

 would be 
\begin_inset Formula $yE$
\end_inset

 in the steady state (
\begin_inset Formula $s\cdot f(k)=\delta+g+n)$
