\begin_layout Section
Lucas Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Effective labour (since the productivity/efficiency of labour improves)
 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{e}=uhL$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u=$
\end_inset

allocation, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=human\ capital$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With production function as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
Y & =AK^{\alpha}(uhL)^{1-\alpha}.
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{e}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{Y}{L_{e}}=A(\frac{K}{L_{e}})^{\alpha}(\frac{uhL}{L_{e}})^{1-\alpha}\Rightarrow\bar{y}=A\bar{k}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 The human capital grows as following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\Delta h & =G(1-u)h^{\gamma}
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\Delta h}{h}=G(1-u)h^{\gamma-1}$
\end_inset

 is constant for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=1$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\Delta h}{h}=G(1-u)$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and implies that human capital (and thus the economy) can grow unbounded.
 In fact, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\ge1$
\end_inset

, the per-capita income would grow without technological progress.
 Notice also that 
\begin_inset Formula $u=1$
\end_inset

 (no allocation to human capital) means the human capital would not grow.
 It also means that 
\begin_inset Formula $u=0$
\end_inset

 would result in human capital growing at the maximal rate 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}=\frac{Y}{uhL}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{k}=\frac{K}{uhL}$
\end_inset

, a policy implication is that increasing time in acquiring skills 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-u)$
\end_inset

 has a permanent impact on human capital (
\begin_inset Formula $h)$
\end_inset

 and output per capita (
\begin_inset Formula $y)$
\end_inset

.
